      <h2>Unpacking &amp; Assembly</h2>
      <p><strong>Tools required:</strong> Tin snips, knife, wrench (unpacking). Hex wrenches (assembly).</p>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>The machine is heavy (304 lbs).</strong> Do not attempt any procedure you feel is unsafe. Seek professional assistance if needed.
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Open the cardboard box, remove the machine base, loose parts, and top foam insert.
          <div class="image-row">
            <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p17_00.jpg" alt="Opening the DP20 shipping box" />
            <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p17_01.jpg" alt="Removing loose parts and foam inserts" />
            <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p17_02.jpg" alt="Machine base removed from packaging" />
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>Cut the box down at the four corners to make it flat. Cut the end of the bottom foam insert to access the column.
          <div class="image-row">
            <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p18_00.jpg" alt="Cutting box corners flat" />
            <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p18_01.jpg" alt="Cutting foam to access column" />
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>Install the base parallel to the headstock using four 3/8 x 1-1/2" hex bolts.
          <div class="image-row">
            <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p18_02.jpg" alt="Base installation with hex bolts" />
            <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p18_03.jpg" alt="Base aligned parallel to headstock" />
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>Install the eye bolt on top of the head assembly. Use cloth lifting straps around the column to lift from horizontal to vertical. <strong>Do NOT use the lifting eye for this step.</strong>
          <div class="image-row">
            <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p19_00.jpg" alt="Eye bolt installation on head assembly" />
            <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p19_01.jpg" alt="Lifting with cloth straps around column" />
            <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p19_02.jpg" alt="Lifting machine from horizontal to vertical" />
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>Lift the DP20 out of the packaging with two or more people.
          <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p20_00.jpg" alt="Lifting DP20 out of packaging" />
        </li>
        <li>Remove plastic coverings and clean anti-rust coatings with a degreaser (e.g., Simple Green). Do not use gasoline or distillates on painted surfaces.</li>
        <li>Clean the arbor, quill, and chuck interior using mineral spirits.</li>
        <li>Remove tape from the arbor height adjustment shaft. Install the depth handle, securing with bolt and washer. The handle can be installed on either side.
          <div class="image-row">
            <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p20_01.jpg" alt="Removing tape from adjustment shaft" />
            <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p20_02.jpg" alt="Installing depth handle with bolt and washer" />
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>Assemble and install the table height adjustment handle using the 3/8 x 4-1/2" hex bolt, pivot handle, and set screw.
          <div class="image-row">
            <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p20_03.jpg" alt="Table height adjustment handle parts" />
            <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p20_04.jpg" alt="Installing table height adjustment handle" />
          </div>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Chuck Installation:</strong> Unplug the machine. Clean the tapered portions of the arbor and the internal taper with mineral spirits. Insert the chuck and arbor assembly and seat with a dead blow mallet (2&ndash;3 sharp strikes). <strong>Never use a steel hammer directly against the arbor or chuck.</strong>
          <div class="image-row">
            <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p20_05.jpg" alt="Chuck and arbor assembly" />
            <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p20_06.jpg" alt="Seating chuck with dead blow mallet" />
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <div class="note">
        The DP20 has a dedicated chuck key holder on the left side of the headstock. The chuck key must be in position for the Auto-Start function to operate, preventing inadvertent starts while using the chuck key.
      </div>

      <h2>Table Adjustments</h2>

      <h3>Table Tilt</h3>
      <p>Disengage the stop stud, loosen the tension nut, and tilt the table to the desired angle. Tighten the tension nut to secure. Some models include a stop stud for a 90-degree quick reference (not for precise alignment).</p>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p21_00.jpg" alt="Table tilt adjustment — stop stud and tension nut" />
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p21_01.jpg" alt="Table tilted to angle" />
      </div>

      <h3>Table Swing</h3>
      <p>Loosen all three column locks and rotate the table around the column. Ensure the rack and locks rotate with the table. Tighten all three column locks when in position.</p>
      <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p22_00.png" alt="Table swing — loosening column locks to rotate table" />

      <h3>Table Height</h3>
      <p>Loosen the column lock on the table support casting and turn the height adjustment handle to move the table. Tighten the column lock to secure.</p>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p22_01.jpg" alt="Column lock on table support casting" />
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p22_02.jpg" alt="Turning the height adjustment handle" />
      </div>

      <h3>Table Insert</h3>
      <p>The removable MDF table insert is held by friction. If the bit contacts it, there is less chance of damage. Adjust flush with the tabletop using the four leveling bolts underneath.</p>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p23_00.jpg" alt="MDF table insert in position" />
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p23_01.jpg" alt="Leveling bolts underneath table insert" />
      </div>

      <h3>Table Clamping</h3>
      <p>The table provides one side-to-side T-slot and two front-to-rear T-slots for clamps, fences, jigs, fixtures, or vises. Ten holes accept clamps with either 5/8" or 16mm posts.</p>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p23_02.jpg" alt="Table T-slots and clamping holes" />
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p24_00.png" alt="Table clamping layout diagram" />
      </div>

      <h2>Electrical Connection</h2>
      <p>The drill press is pre-wired with a 110V 3-pin plug. Connect to a 15-amp (min.) dedicated circuit.</p>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>GFCI/GFI not recommended.</strong> The motor's electronic speed control, reverse, and auto-reverse functions cause frequency variations that GFCI devices may interpret as faults, causing nuisance tripping. Check local codes for exceptions.
      </div>

      <h2>Control Panel</h2>
      <p>The touch screen control panel manages all basic functions and programmable operations.</p>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p25_00.jpg" alt="DP20 touch screen control panel overview" />
        <figcaption>Touch screen control panel</figcaption>
      </div>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p26_00.jpg" alt="Control panel button layout with numbered labels" />
        <figcaption>Control panel button layout</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h3>Button Functions</h3>
      <p>Each button has a teal/blue indicator bar. When illuminated, the feature is active.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Motor ON/OFF:</strong> Starts and stops the drill motor. In Auto Start mode, the motor won't start until the quill handle is pulled down.</li>
        <li><strong>Tone:</strong> Toggles the audible button-press confirmation. Defaults to On at power-up.</li>
        <li><strong>LED:</strong> Toggles the work light illuminating the table area.</li>
        <li><strong>Laser:</strong> Toggles the crosshair laser locator.</li>
        <li><strong>Speed:</strong> Sets RPM in programming mode. Range: 60&ndash;3600 RPM. Adjust with the selector knob.</li>
        <li><strong>Depth:</strong> Sets drilling depth in programming mode, most often used for tapping with Auto Reverse.</li>
        <li><strong>Error Indicator:</strong> Displays error codes (e.g., exceeding 600 RPM with Auto Reverse, Error 9 for chuck key removal).</li>
        <li><strong>Zero:</strong> Sets the depth display to zero at the material surface. Drill depth shows as negative values.</li>
        <li><strong>Program:</strong> Toggles between Manual and Program mode. Short press to select saved programs (P1&ndash;P5). Long press to enter programming mode and save settings.</li>
        <li><strong>Program Indicator:</strong> Shows the selected program number (P1&ndash;P5).</li>
        <li><strong>Reverse:</strong> Toggles forward/reverse rotation for left-handed bits or other uses.</li>
        <li><strong>Inch/mm:</strong> Cycles between decimal inches, fractional inches, and millimeters.</li>
        <li><strong>Increment Indicators:</strong> Shows the active measurement unit.</li>
        <li><strong>Auto Start:</strong> When active, the spindle starts automatically when pulling the quill handle. The chuck key must be in the holder. Motor ON/OFF must be in the ON position.</li>
        <li><strong>Auto Reverse:</strong> Reverses the spindle at the preset depth. RPM limited to 600 for tap safety.</li>
        <li><strong>Live Depth Display:</strong> Shows actual depth during quill travel.</li>
        <li><strong>Load Meter:</strong> Displays motor load. Red zone indicates excessive load &mdash; stop and inspect bit, material, and RPM.</li>
        <li><strong>Speed Display:</strong> Shows the selected RPM.</li>
        <li><strong>Depth Setting Display:</strong> Shows the desired depth in Program mode.</li>
      </ol>

