      <h3>Quill Zero Setting</h3>
      <p>On initial setup, the Live Depth display should read 0.00 with the quill at the top of the stroke. If not:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Check for debris above/below the rubber washer on the quill. Clean with a cloth if needed.</li>
        <li>Cycle power off and on. After the boot screen clears, simultaneously press the <strong>Depth</strong> and <strong>Laser</strong> buttons momentarily, then release.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>To restore the original (non-zero) reading, simultaneously press <strong>Speed</strong> and <strong>Laser</strong> buttons.</p>

      <h3>Error Codes</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Error 9:</strong> Chuck key is removed from the holder. Auto Start is disabled until the key is returned. The drill press operates normally otherwise.</li>
        <li><strong>Audible Error:</strong> Auto Reverse is selected with RPM above 600. Reduce RPM to 600 or less, or deselect Auto Reverse.</li>
        <li><strong>Other Errors:</strong> May indicate communication errors, open circuits, or voltage issues. Contact Laguna Customer Service.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Programming</h2>
      <p>The DP20 supports 5 programmable presets (P1&ndash;P5) for repeatable operations like tapping.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Short press the Program button to enter program mode.</li>
        <li>Rotate the selector knob to choose the program number.</li>
        <li>Long press the Program button until it flashes.</li>
        <li>Set RPM: press Speed, rotate selector knob, confirm with a press.</li>
        <li>Set zero point: lower bit to material surface, press Zero.</li>
        <li>Set depth: press Depth, rotate selector knob, confirm with a press.</li>
        <li>Toggle Auto Start, Auto Reverse, and other settings as needed.</li>
        <li>Short press Program to save and exit.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>RPM / Drill Speed Selection</h2>
      <p>Press the <strong>Speed</strong> button on the Control Panel (the indicator bar flashes), then rotate the Control Knob to the desired RPM. Speed range: 60&ndash;3600 RPM.</p>

      <div class="note">
        <strong>General rules:</strong> Smaller bits require higher RPM. Softer materials use higher RPM; harder materials use slower RPM. Auto Reverse is limited to 600 RPM to prevent tap breakage.
      </div>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p33_00.jpg" alt="RPM selection chart — recommended speeds by material and bit size" />
        <figcaption>Recommended RPM by material and bit size</figcaption>
      </div>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p34_00.png" alt="Drill speed reference table — wood" />
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p35_00.png" alt="Drill speed reference table — metal and other materials" />
      </div>

      <h3>Drill Bits</h3>
      <p>Consider hole size/depth, material hardness, bit material/coating, and sharpness when selecting bits. Bits can break from over-feeding, being dull, incorrect RPM, or skipping on entry.</p>
      <h3>Installing &amp; Removing a Drill Bit</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Disconnect power.</li>
        <li>Loosen the chuck with the key.</li>
        <li>Place the bit into the center of the chuck.</li>
        <li>Tighten the chuck with the key. Ensure jaws do not contact the flutes.</li>
        <li>Place the key into the magnetic holder. <strong>Never leave the key in the chuck.</strong></li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Depth Stop</h2>
      <p>With the machine off and drill bit installed, lower the bit to the desired depth. While holding that position, tighten the Depth Stop Locking Knob.</p>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p36_00.jpg" alt="Depth stop mechanism — lowering bit to desired depth" />
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p36_01.jpg" alt="Tightening the depth stop locking knob" />
      </div>

      <h2>Laser Light</h2>
      <p>The crosshair laser locator shows where the drill bit will engage the material. Toggle via the Laser button on the Control Panel.</p>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Never look at the source of laser light.</strong> Eye damage is possible.
      </div>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p36_02.png" alt="Laser crosshair alignment on workpiece" />
        <figcaption>Crosshair laser locator</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h3>Laser Adjustment</h3>
      <p>The lasers are factory pre-set but may shift during shipping. After assembly:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Level and lock the table horizontally. Install a small drill bit.</li>
        <li><strong>Vertical adjustment:</strong> Use a board with a perpendicular pencil line. Adjust the vertical screw on each laser emitter to align with the line.</li>
        <li><strong>Crosshair alignment:</strong> Place the board flat, lower the bit to make a dimple, then adjust the crosshair screw on each laser to align over the dimple.</li>
        <li>Re-check vertical alignment after crosshair adjustments.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p37_00.jpg" alt="Laser vertical adjustment screw on emitter" />
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p38_00.jpg" alt="Laser crosshair alignment over drill dimple" />
      </div>

      <h2>Using the Drill Press</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Install the desired drill bit or tap. Tighten chuck with key, replace key in holder.</li>
        <li>Adjust table height, swing, and angle. Tighten all locks.</li>
        <li>Turn on LED light if needed.</li>
        <li>Position and clamp workpiece (use T-slots and holes for clamps).</li>
        <li>Turn on laser if using for positioning.</li>
        <li>Set and lock depth stop if required.</li>
        <li>Confirm main power is on and E-Stop is disengaged.</li>
        <li>Select program or adjust RPM.</li>
        <li>Turn on the chuck. Wait for actual RPM to match selected RPM.</li>
        <li>Engage bit with smooth, even pressure.</li>
        <li>Return handle to resting position when complete.</li>
        <li>Turn off chuck. Ensure rotation has stopped before removing workpiece.</li>
        <li>Turn off laser, light, and main power when finished.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Maintenance</h2>
      <p>Use Teflon-based lubricant rather than regular oil, as Teflon dries and accumulates less dirt and dust.</p>

      <h3>Chuck &amp; Arbor Removal</h3>
      <p>Unplug the machine. Lower the quill to expose the slot. Align the slots by rotating the chuck. Insert the drift key and tap sharply with a dead blow mallet until the chuck and arbor loosen. Hold the chuck to prevent it from falling.</p>
      <img src="/manuals/laguna-dp20/p38_01.png" alt="Chuck and arbor removal — drift key insertion point" />

      <h3>Table Insert</h3>
      <p>Replace the MDF insert if the hole becomes too large or it is damaged. Adjust the four leveling bolts so the insert is flush with the table surface.</p>

      <h3>Bearings</h3>
      <p>All bearings are sealed for life and require no maintenance. Replace if faulty.</p>

      <h3>Preventing Rust</h3>
      <p>Coat non-painted cast iron surfaces (table) with wax or protectant. Lubricate moving surfaces (guides, rack and pinion) with Teflon-based lubricant.</p>

      <h3>Table Squaring</h3>
      <p>Use the reference stop stud for quick 90-degree alignment. Pull the stud away, loosen the tension nut to tilt, and re-tighten to hold position.</p>

      <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>
      <h3>Drill Press Will Not Start</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Check that the power cord is plugged in.</li>
        <li>Check that the start switch is fully lifted (back of headstock).</li>
        <li>Check that the yellow safety plug is fully engaged.</li>
        <li>Check that the E-Stop button is disengaged (front of headstock).</li>
        <li>Check that the ON switch on the Control Panel is on and lit.</li>
        <li>Check/reset the breaker. Verify correct power: 110&ndash;120V, 15 amp min.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Machine Will Not Stop</h3>
      <p>Disconnect from power immediately and do not run until repaired. Check the stop switch and internal breaker.</p>

      <h3>Bit Overheats</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Dull bit &mdash; replace or sharpen.</li>
        <li>Excessive RPM &mdash; reduce speed.</li>
        <li>Excessive feed rate &mdash; slow down.</li>
        <li>Lubricant required for the application.</li>
        <li>Incorrect bit type &mdash; change to correct type.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Machine Vibrates</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Machine not level &mdash; re-level on the floor.</li>
        <li>Bearings worn &mdash; replace.</li>
      </ul>

